x4freetext: Review.
The approach  used  to evaluate the cross sections is
based  on  the  assumption   that   the   systematic
differences in experiments have a much weaker effect
on the general characteristics of the cross sections
such  as  the  integrated  cross  sections  and  the
centres of gravity as compared with  the  individual
values of cross sections. Using the data for 238U in
the nearbarrier energy range (E(gamma) =  5-8  MeV),
it  was  shown that while the average total error in
the weighted-mean cross section is  about  30%,  the
average  total error in the integrated weighted-mean
cross section is 1-2%.  Similar estimates  are  made
for  other  energy  ranges  as  well  in the case of
235,238U and other nuclei.  The main  principles  of
the  cross section evaluation algorithm are briefly:
- the  data  are  selected  which  are  obtained  by
reliable techniques and  for  which the absolute
values (or the methods of their  estimation), the
statistical  errors are given (or estimated);
- using  the  statistical  criteria,  the  data  are
selected   whose  integrated  cross  sections  and
centres of gravity do not differ greatly from  the
weightedmean values;
- when the iterative  procedure  of  renormalization
(correction  of  the  scale  in  the cross section
axis) and recalibration (correction of  the  scale
in energy axis) are used,  the data are reduced to
the form of the  best  agreement  of  the  general
characteristics;  in  this case the consistency of
He data is controlled  by  using  the  generalized
criteria  of  chi**2;  the procedure is being done
till one of the following conditions begins to  Be
fulfilled:
1) the  data  distribution begins to correspond to
their       individual        errors        and
r**2=chi**2/(K-n)=1,  where (K-n) is the number
of degrees of freedom;
2) the  integrated cross section and the centre of
gravity of the  corrected  weighted-mean  cross
section  begins  to  decrease  from the initial
value by more than 1 root-mean-square error;
3) the parameter r**2 decrease rate becomes < 1%;
- the values of the  renormalized  and  recalibrated
cross  sections  are  combined  into  a single set
whose  values  at  every  point  is  checked   for
consistency  with  the other (the values providing
anomalously large contribution to the total chi**2
sum are discarded);
- the set of the values that have satisfied all  the
selections  and  its  errors by means of reduction
method.
